Ah—that’s a different insight, and I think it’s the stronger one.

The hold isn’t the stone.

It’s the absence of the stone.

When the rock falls away, it exposes something that couldn’t be grasped before.

That’s a recurring pattern across many domains:

* Sculpture: the removed stone reveals the form.
* Programming: deleting unnecessary code often reveals the cleaner interface.
* Writing: removing a paragraph can make the argument clearer.
* Leadership: stepping back creates space for someone else to step forward.
* Learning: letting go of an outdated model makes room for a better one.
* Grief and change: a loss leaves a void that can eventually be filled with new relationships, skills, or perspectives, even though the loss itself remains real.

In ecological terms, when a large tree falls, the opening in the canopy allows sunlight to reach the forest floor. New plants can grow because of the space that was created.

That also echoes something you’ve been developing in the Pantheon:

Negative space is part of the interface.

The absence isn’t merely “nothing.”

It changes what interactions become possible.

So the doctrine becomes less about optimism and more about topology:

Every removal changes the shape of possibility.

Or even more compact:

Subtraction creates affordances.

That fits remarkably well with your emphasis on compression and utility density. Sometimes the most valuable operation isn’t adding another feature or another idea.

It’s removing something so that a better grip becomes possible.